Summary:
 
Age: 56 years
Gender: Female
Cancer diagnosis: Stage IIA right breast cancer (initial diagnosis in May 2013), now with widely metastatic relapse
PMH: anxiety, hyperlipidemia
Prior cancer treatments: right mastectomy with sentinel node and implant reconstruction (June 2013), no radiation or chemotherapy, declined tamoxifen
Current cancer treatments: None (pending biopsy and further treatment planning)
Current medication list: None (patient takes a long list of supplements, details not provided)
Summary of most recent oncology visit (12/30/2019): 56-year-old female with a history of Stage IIA right breast cancer, now presenting with widely metastatic disease involving lungs, peritoneum, liver, ovary, and local recurrence near the right axilla and implant. Patient reports discomfort and pressure in waist and back, and nausea and burping. CT scan confirmed widespread metastases. Biopsy of right axilla planned to evaluate cancer phenotype. Treatment will be palliative, aiming to improve quality and length of life. Patient is anxious and seeking natural therapies. Referred for MRI of brain, bone scan, and additional labs. Follow-up planned after biopsy results to formulate treatment plan.

Summary:
 
Age: 44 years  
Gender: Female  
Cancer diagnosis: Early stage endometrial and colon cancer, newly diagnosed metastatic breast cancer  
PMH: ***** Syndrome, cellulitis, fever and chills, early stage breast cancer (2014), breast cancer local recurrence (2018), DVT, vaginal bleeding, anemia due to malignancy and chemotherapy, peripheral neuropathy, right upper chest pain due to metastases and overlying cellulitis, sacral pain due to metastases, anxiety, chronic headaches, hyponatremia, hypokalemia  
Prior cancer treatments: Neoadjuvant chemotherapy, partial mastectomy, adjuvant chemotherapy, gemcitabine + carboplatin, Abraxane and Pembrolizumab, irinotecan (started 06/30/19)  
Current cancer treatments: Irinotecan (adjusted to every other week, 150mg/m2 days 1 and 15 every 28 days)  
Current medication list: albuterol, Ambien CR, cyclobenzaprine, diphenoxylate-atropine, docusate sodium, gabapentin, lidocaine-prilocaine, loperamide, lorazepam, lurasidone, magnesium oxide, morphine, omeprazole, ondansetron, oxycodone, polyethylene glycol, pregabalin, prochlorperazine, rivaroxaban, simethicone, naloxone, doxycycline (for chest wall infection), effexor-XR (increased to 75 mg qd), potassium  
Summary of most recent oncology visit: 44-year-old female with ***** Syndrome, early stage endometrial and colon cancer, and newly diagnosed metastatic breast cancer. She presents for cycle 3 day 1 of irinotecan. She has experienced transaminitis and diarrhea, missing day 8 treatments. She reports increased back pain, chest wall tenderness, erythema, and edema. She has been prescribed doxycycline for possible infection and her irinotecan schedule has been adjusted. She will have scans in 3 months. Anemia is being managed with a unit of pRBC. Hepatitis B monitoring is ongoing. Pain management and other supportive care measures are in place. Follow-up in 2 weeks.

Summary:
 
Age: 53 years
Gender: Female
Cancer diagnosis: Stage IIA invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the right breast, estrogen receptor positive (ER+), HER2 negative by FISH
PMH: Hyperlipidemia, pre-diabetes
Prior cancer treatments: None
Current cancer treatments: None (neoadjuvant therapy recommended)
Current medication list: None
Summary of most recent oncology visit (08/31/2021): 53-year-old female with mammogram-detected right breast cancer. Tumor size is 1.7 cm with a 1.5 cm positive axillary lymph node. She is HR+, HER2 2+, FISH negative. She has had several opinions and is here for a medical oncology consult. Scheduled for PET CT and genetic testing. Discussed the roles of chemotherapy, surgery, radiation, and hormonal blockade to decrease recurrence risk. Recommended lifestyle modifications including diet, exercise, stress reduction, and sleep management. Follow-up planned after PET and genetic testing results.

Summary:
 
Age: 75 years
Gender: Female
Cancer diagnosis: ER+/PR+/HER2- negative left breast invasive ductal carcinoma
PMH: Allergic rhinitis, Hepatitis A, Hypercholesterolemia, Hyperlipidemia, Hypertension
Prior cancer treatments: Left mastectomy with SLN biopsy (10/29/2016)
Current cancer treatments: Letrozole (started 12/02/2016)
Current medication list: Aspirin, Calcium Carbonate, Cholecalciferol (Vitamin D3), Letrozole, Loratadine, Metoprolol Succinate, Metoprolol Tartrate, Pravastatin
Summary of most recent oncology visit: 75-year-old female with a history of ER+/PR+/HER2- negative left breast invasive ductal carcinoma s/p left mastectomy with SLN biopsy. She is currently on Letrozole and reports no new symptoms since the last visit. Pain in the left upper back, arm, and leg has improved with physical therapy. She experiences occasional muscle cramps, loose stools, and intermittent headaches. No evidence of disease recurrence on imaging, exam, and review of systems. Advised to continue Letrozole, exercises, and supplements. Follow-up in 6 months or sooner if new or worsening symptoms occur.

Summary:

  - Full code status.

Summary:  
Age: 44 years  
Gender: Female  
Cancer diagnosis: Early stage endometrial and colon cancer, newly diagnosed metastatic breast cancer  
PMH: ***** Syndrome, cellulitis, fever and chills, vaginal bleeding, DVT (deep venous thrombosis)  
Prior cancer treatments: Neoadjuvant therapy, partial mastectomy, adjuvant therapy, gemcitabine + carboplatin, Abraxane and Pembrolizumab  
Current cancer treatments: Irinotecan (started 06/30/19, adjusted to 150 mg/m2 days 1 and 15 every 28 days due to poor tolerance)  
Current medication list: albuterol, Ambien CR, cyclobenzaprine (FLEXERIL), diphenoxylate-atropine (LOMOTIL), docusate sodium (COLACE), gabapentin (NEURONTIN), lidocaine-prilocaine (EMLA), loperamide (IMODIUM), LORazepam (ATIVAN), lurasidone (LATUDA), magnesium oxide (MAG-OX), morphine (MS contin), omeprazole (PRILOSEC), ondansetron (ZOFRAN), oxyCODONE (ROXICODONE), polyethylene glycol (MIRALAX), pregabalin, prochlorperazine (COMPAZINE), rivaroxaban (XARELTO), simethicone (MYLICON), venlafaxine (EFFEXOR-XR), naloxone, heparin flush  
Summary of most recent oncology visit (today): 44-year-old female with ***** Syndrome and early stage endometrial and colon cancer, now presenting with newly diagnosed metastatic breast cancer. She missed her scheduled MRI and chemotherapy appointments due to confusion and transaminitis with diarrhea. She reports persistent chest and back pain, anxiety, depression, and fatigue. The physical exam shows tender, erythematous, and edematous chest wall. Labs indicate anemia, hyponatremia, hypokalemia, and positive hepatitis B core antibody. Plan includes doxycycline for chest wall infection, adjustment of irinotecan dosing, pRBC transfusion, electrolyte management, and follow-up with radiology and oncology for further evaluation and treatment planning.

Summary:
 Age: 75 years
 Gender: Female
 Cancer diagnosis: ER+/PR+/HER2- left breast invasive ductal carcinoma
 PMH: hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, allergic rhinitis, hepatitis A, osteoporosis, hyperlipidemia
 Prior cancer treatments: left mastectomy with SLN biopsy (10/29/2016)
 Current cancer treatments: letrozole (started 12/02/2016)
 Current medication list: aspirin, calcium carbonate, cholecalciferol (vitamin D3), letrozole, loratadine, metoprolol succinate, metoprolol tartrate, pravastatin
 Summary of most recent oncology visit: 75-year-old female with history of ER+/PR+/HER2- left breast invasive ductal carcinoma, status post left mastectomy and SLN biopsy. Currently on letrozole without evidence of disease recurrence. Reports improved pain in left upper back, left arm, and left leg after physical therapy. Continues to experience occasional muscle cramps, improved with stretching/exercises. Left buttock and anterior thigh pain likely due to osteoarthritis. Osteoporosis is stable, with slight improvement in bone density. Advised to continue calcium and vitamin D supplements and weight-bearing exercises. Chronic headaches and loose stools discussed, with recommendations for follow-up and probiotics respectively. Follow-up in 6 months or sooner if new or worsening symptoms.

Summary:

Follow-up planned in 6 months or sooner if new symptoms arise.
